<p>
      It turns out that Fawn’s second moon had been a silver cannonball, whistling high overhead.
</p>
<p>
      The fire responsibly doused, PeeGee caught up with Comet. He reached out, grabbed <%= @user.characterfirstname %>, and swung the page onto his back, while Comet did the same with Fawn.
</p>
<p>
      “Legitimate guildmasters coordinate the exchange by flags,” said PeeGee. “These motherfuckers are ingot flinging out of season, and doing so blindly.”
</p>
<p>
      “If they’re doing this illegally, why don’t they just make a little extra effort and bring the ingots close to each other, like normal tradespeople?”
</p>
<p class="has-side-note">
  “What’s the fun in that?” asked PeeGee, kicking into a higher gear and rattling out in front of Comet. Not to be outdone, Comet sprinted hard as hell, barely breaking a sweat, which disappointed Fawn, who had been looking forward to licking her neck.
<p class="side-note" style="border-left: 5px solid #66023c">"It’s salt, not assault.”--Ancient deer saying.
</p>
<p>
      They were really hauling now. Comet was so athletic that her armor barely clanked, even though she was really digging into the rutted path. Still, Fawn felt it helpful to focus on her own moon, which hung constant in a night sky filling with smoke.
</p>
<p>
      Suddenly a shape ran out in front of them. It occluded the moon. It occluded Fawn’s personal moon, which never happened. A personal moon shown from every surface that you looked up to at night, even from the corner of prison cells. In ancient times, they would interrogate political prisoners about their personal moons, making them mix pigments until they reached their matched their moon. The captors would paint the cells over with this shade,
      so that even rabid dissidents would feel utterly alone, divorced from their own reality. Once they emerged, from however long a sentence, they become obsessed with seeing their moon, nouveau lunatics running wild in a cruel world, their ideology forgotten. To not be able to see you own moon has since been outlawed as a form of punishment. It’s considered inhumane. But what covered Fawn’s moon turned out to be so much more.
</p>
<p>
      A breathing bank of storm clouds, a bristly eclipse. It was the Butterfly Boar, crossing in front of them. Now, the boar is twelve feet tall at the withers, and Comet is eight feet tall, and Fawn had her arms around Comet’s shoulders. So the boar didn’t seem that big. I mean it was big, don’t get me wrong. But for Fawn, being on Comet's shoulders allowed her to indulge in the luxury of awe, instead of merely being an addict of cheap fear.
</p>
<p>
      She could see the boar’s tusks—smooth and polished pawns. She could see golden grapeshot pulsing in an open wound. The boar had been rousted from chowing down on barley slurry in the gutters that lined the mills on the outskirts of the Ingot Exchange. And the smell! Good gracious. The boar had just become obsessed with crabapples, and his hide was thick with them. There were a couple hundred impaled on a big thatch on his side, where he had rolled around in a sacked orchard three weeks ago. Now they hung there, fermenting, the smelled like PeeGee did when he put out the fire.
</p>
<p>
      The boar moved like lava, or a tidal wave, or a tornado. Too big to be as fast as it was when you got up close. Good lord it was quick, and surprisingly quiet. And stinky. I mean, whew!
</p>
<p>
      And just like that he had crossed the path and was running through the field on the other side, the enormous ridge of his back cutting through the wheat like a black fin through the Hypersea. His chrysalis clinked along behind him at great speed, it seemed as if the chain had been sucked up by the field like steel spaghetti. Inside the chrysalis was a fetal butterfly, glowing green, curled in on itself, its features blunted by its heretofore incomplete gestation.
<p>
      It was gone before PeeGee and Comet could even think to stop. They continued running on until they reached the end of the field, and crashed thirty yards into the forest beyond. They paused to catch their breath, turned around and watched the bandits expel their store of precious metals in a great and glittering cacophony of favorable rates.
</p>
<p>
      The next morning they made it to the bar at the base of Mount Oligarch. Stools squeaked to see a dusty, chaff-bedraggled Fawn white-belly up to the bar and order three shots of Confidante.
</p>
